dismissalComment.html: full and follows Porterfield again, who is stepping to leg this time, he's ended up yorked well outside leg stump and the ball cannons into the stumps. Bit unfortunate for Porterfield but well bowled Rankin, realising the batsman had stepped away and followed him to cramp him up, it was a good full, straight delivery and Porterfield was nowhere near it

dismissalComment.html: full and straight, Mooney misses and is given out lbw it looked very straight that. Good pace from Rankin, the batsman hurried in trying to play to leg and misses, caught very low on the pad in front of middle. Slight question over whether it might have pitched just outside leg but it was so full it's very hard to tell and looked very straight

dismissalComment.html: stays back and attempts to run the ball to third man - but Wright has played on! The slowness of the pitch did for him, cross-batted shots always dangerous in these circumstances and a thick bottom edge sent the ball straight down on to the base of off stump. Wright's head sags in unison, he kicks the turf - Ireland are right on top here

tries to leave, doesn't withdraw the bat quickly enough and there's a feather on it - Ballance is gone, caught behind! Indecision from Ballance, facing only his second ball, he wanted to leave but his muscles took a moment to catch up with his brain and the ball brushed the face on its way through

skids on, through the defences and bowled him! Murtagh has a third, England's little man defeated by one that came back at him - though in truth it was a loose shot, left a gap between bat and pad and Murtagh located it

dismissalComment.html: pitched up and swinging in, hit in front again - and that's out! Carberry manages just 10 runs in atonement for his two drops (plus 0-12 with the ball) and his ODI debut is ended by a man who has played 66 of them with distinction for Ireland. Johnston got the right line to a left-hander, the ball pitching on middle, holding its line and would have lopped the top of the pole

commentTextItems.html: and there it is, Dockrell is launched over the deep midwicket fence again, Morgan capping a superb fightback to secure England's six-wicket win with yet another six!

commentPostTextItems.html: 6.15pm: We've had a barrel-load of entertainment today, if not quite the famous mugging we thought was in prospect. England's B team were strong enough, though you might equally say that Ireland were beaten by Ireland's best. Anyway, thanks for your comments, we'll be back for the one-day series against Australia later in the week. Cheerio

6.05pm: Time for the presentations, then. Ireland captain, William Porterfield: "Thanks, it was nice to get a hundred, shame to come out on the losing side. I obviously felt all right, playing England in the Irish jersey is always special, nice to get a score in a game like this. We fancied our chances, bowling with sustained pressure. We felt the way Tredders bowled, the spinners would come into the game but once the ball got softer it was hard for them - credit to Morgs and Ravi. It doesn't matter who gets the wickets for them. The crowd were fantastic, especially when we were looking for a wicket to break the partnership."

England's captain and Man of the Match, Eoin Morgan: "Yeah, I was probably more nervous sitting in the changing rooms than out in the middle. Was nice to get out there, it was tough, quite challenging, and a lot of what we're not used to as a side. It's been magnificent to get some runs under my belt and contribute to an England win. Time in the middle is crucial ahead of a big series [against Australia]. It's been an incredible day for Irish cricket, so congratulations to Cricket Ireland. Boyd had to bowl fuller, which is quite challenging, but he handled it well. The pitch was quite tricky to start with but the nerves would be expected from the new guys coming in. You only had to look at the crowd today, the support has been brilliant."

5.55pm: At 48 for 4, this did not look like being a good day to be English but, in the end, England's pocket rocket Irishman captained his side out of a corner and helped deny his countrymen a famous win in the process. Morgan was matched by Bopara, who looked good from the off and grew into a sparkling innings: the two old stagers, relatively speaking, saving England's greenhorns after the green shirts had turned the top order into grass. Their unbroken stand of 226 set a new fifth-wicket record in ODIs. Credit will rightly shower down on Ireland, though, for having pushed England so hard for 80% of the game; for having staged a cracking match in front of an appreciative crowd; and, not least, for having produced two of the three century-makers. They also had a hand in England's bowling success, with Boyd Rankin taking four-for - though Lambeth's Tim Murtagh returned the favour during the England innings.

commentPreTextItems.html: Brilliant performance from these two and it's put down the very strong prospect of an Irish upset

commentTextItems.html: full toss, sweeps through backward square, picks out and man and that will just be a single

commentPostTextItems.html: One more blow will seal it...

commentTextItems.html: makes room and drills the ball over extra cover, another meaty connection and the ball bounces to the rope - that's Ravi Bopara's century, his first in one-day internationals
smashed back down the ground, right out of the screws and the ball disappears flat over long-on for the eighth six of the England innings, all scored by these two!
little bit short, on leg stump and heaved over midwicket, there's no one out there and Bopara is into the nineties

commentPreTextItems.html: "It must be quite rare in any form of cricket for opposing captains to both reach centuries with a six. I'd bet good money it's unique in ODIs." I won't be wagering against you, Tony

commentTextItems.html: attempts to clear the ropes again, slogging a full ball towards deep square leg, doesn't have the legs though and Niall O'Brien settles underneath it only to drop the chance. Oh dear
this comes out wrong, low full toss on leg stump and Bopara wristily flicks the ball to the rope at deep backward square leg
leaves his crease and hacks across the line, gets one through midwicket
steps out and pushes a length ball into the covers
angled across, tapped back to the bowler

commentPostTextItems.html: "So two IRISH men scored a century today and yet England is going to win then..." That's about the size of it, Amarish Patel. Bopara might get an authentic, born-and-bred ton, too

commentTextItems.html: steps away, Sorensen follows him and Bopara lofts uppishly down the ground for a single to long-on

commentPreTextItems.html: Sorensen back on. This is turning into another captain Morgan's spiced run chase...

commentTextItems.html: length ball, stays back and pulls flat through midwicket to the sweeper
opens the face and steers one more through point

commentPostTextItems.html: "@James & Gardner - The English don't have exclusive rights over self-deprecation, my good sires. It was a joke." You are fully absolved, Aditya

commentTextItems.html: excellent pick up, spots the slower ball on a length outside off and belabours it over midwicket for another six

commentPreTextItems.html: The wheels just threatening to fall off the Ireland battlewagon now...

commentTextItems.html: pitched up outside off, pushed to mid-off and they race through for a single
slower-ball bouncer, I think, Bopara didn't quite pick it but neither did Wilson and it runs away for extras
brutal, straight back down the ground this time, high follow through and the ball explodes off the face of the bat for another boundary
sixer! Bopara has hit this like Jack Nicklaus on the 18th tee, picking up a full-length ball and pulling it high over deep midwicket for another huge maximum
little bit short, goes back and pierces the off-side field for one into the deep

commentPostTextItems.html: This is now England's highest fifth-wicket partnership in ODIs

commentTextItems.html: floated up, much more air, down the leg side, though

dismissalComment.html: full and straight, Mooney misses and is given out lbw it looked very straight that. Good pace from Rankin, the batsman hurried in trying to play to leg and misses, caught very low on the pad in front of middle. Slight question over whether it might have pitched just outside leg but it was so full it's very hard to tell and looked very straight

headshotImage.caption: Trent Johnston player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Trent Johnston player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Michael Carberry lbw b Johnston 10 (13b 2x4 0x6 12m) SR: 76.92

dismissalComment.html: pitched up and swinging in, hit in front again - and that's out! Carberry manages just 10 runs in atonement for his two drops (plus 0-12 with the ball) and his ODI debut is ended by a man who has played 66 of them with distinction for Ireland. Johnston got the right line to a left-hander, the ball pitching on middle, holding its line and would have lopped the top of the pole

headshotImage.caption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Luke Wright b Murtagh 5 (20b 1x4 0x6 36m) SR: 25

dismissalComment.html: stays back and attempts to run the ball to third man - but Wright has played on! The slowness of the pitch did for him, cross-batted shots always dangerous in these circumstances and a thick bottom edge sent the ball straight down on to the base of off stump. Wright's head sags in unison, he kicks the turf - Ireland are right on top here

headshotImage.caption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: James Taylor b Murtagh 25 (42b 3x4 0x6 53m) SR: 59.52

dismissalComment.html: skids on, through the defences and bowled him! Murtagh has a third, England's little man defeated by one that came back at him - though in truth it was a loose shot, left a gap between bat and pad and Murtagh located it

headshotImage.caption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Gary Ballance c Wilson b Murtagh 0 (2b 0x4 0x6 3m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: tries to leave, doesn't withdraw the bat quickly enough and there's a feather on it - Ballance is gone, caught behind! Indecision from Ballance, facing only his second ball, he wanted to leave but his muscles took a moment to catch up with his brain and the ball brushed the face on its way through

dismissalText.commentary: Eoin Morgan not out 124 (106b 8x4 4x6 147m) SR: 116.98
Ravi Bopara not out 101 (75b 10x4 5x6 116m) SR: 134.66

milestones.description: Porterfield has become the top scorer for IRE in ODIs with 1993 runs, going past Kevin O'Brien's 1907
Ravi Bopara and Eoin Morgan's 226-run partnership is ENG's highest for the 5th wicket in ODIs, breaking the record of 174 between Paul Collingwood and Flintoff
Ravi Bopara and Eoin Morgan's 226-run partnership is the highest for the 5th wicket in ODIs, breaking the record of 223 between Azharuddin and Ajay Jadeja
Porterfield has scored 6 hundreds in ODIs, the most for IRE breaking Paul Stirling's record
